<big><b>ANCIENT EGYPT</b></big>

Ancient Egypt was one of the greatest civilizations in history.

It developed near the Nile River in northeastern Africa more than 5,000 years ago.

The Nile River was very important because it provided:

• Water
• Food
• Transportation
• Fertile land for farming


<big><b>The Pharaohs</b></big>

The rulers of Egypt were called <b>pharaohs</b>.

Egyptians believed that pharaohs were both political and religious leaders.

Some famous pharaohs were:

• Tutankhamun
• Ramses II
• Cleopatra

Examples:
• Pharaohs controlled the army and the government.
• They also supervised the construction of temples and pyramids.


<big><b>The Pyramids</b></big>

The pyramids were giant stone structures built as tombs for pharaohs.

The most famous pyramids are located at Giza.

The Great Pyramid of Giza is one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.

Examples:
• Workers transported huge stones across the desert.
• The pyramids represented power and religion.


<big><b>Egyptian Writing</b></big>

Ancient Egyptians used a writing system called <b>hieroglyphics</b>.

They wrote on papyrus using symbols and pictures.

Examples:
• Priests and scribes learned to read and write.
• Hieroglyphics were used in temples and monuments.


<big><b>Religion and Beliefs</b></big>

Egyptians believed in many gods.

Some important gods were:

• Ra – god of the sun
• Anubis – god of mummification
• Osiris – god of the afterlife

They believed in life after death and preserved bodies through mummification.


<big><b>Daily Life in Egypt</b></big>

Most Egyptians were farmers.

They grew crops such as:

• Wheat
• Barley
• Vegetables

People also worked as:

• Builders
• Soldiers
• Merchants
• Artists

Examples:
• Children helped their families.
• Markets were important centers of trade.

<big><b>Interesting Facts</b></big>

• The Egyptian civilization lasted for thousands of years.
• The Nile River floods helped agriculture.
• Cats were considered sacred animals.
• Egyptian medicine was advanced for its time.

